32.1 Components of a Bayesian Model ðŸŽ¥
\begin{aligned}
y_i \mid \mu,\sigma &\stackrel{iid}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma^2) \\
\mu &\sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_0,\sigma_0^2) \\
\sigma^2 &\sim \mathcal{IG}(\alpha_0,\beta_0)
\end{aligned}
\tag{32.1}
In lesson one, we defined a statistical model as a mathematical structure used to imitate or approximate the data generating process. It incorporates uncertainty and variability using the theory of probability. A model could be very simple, involving only one variable.
A model can be as simple as the one right here or as complicated and sophisticated as we need to capture the behavior of the data. So far, this model is the same for Frequentists and Bayesians.
As you may recall from the previous course, the frequentist approach to fitting this model would be to consider \mu and \sigma to be fixed but unknown constants, and then we would estimate them. To calculate our uncertainty in those estimates a frequentist approach would consider how much the estimates of \mu and \sigma might change if we were to repeat the sampling process and obtain another sample of 15 men, over, and over.
In the rest of this segment, weâ€™re going to review the three key components of Bayesian models, that were used extensively in the previous course. These three primary components of Bayesian models which we often work with are:
\mathbb{P}r(y\mid \theta)\ \text{(likelihood)}
\mathbb{P}r(\theta)\ \text{(prior)}
\mathbb{P}r(y,\theta) = \underbrace{\mathbb{P}r(\theta)}_{prior} \cdot
                        \underbrace{\mathbb{P}r(y \mid \theta)}_{likelihood}
                        \qquad \text{(joint probability)}
\mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y)\ \text{(posterior)}
The posterior distribution is the distribution of \mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y), i.e.Â \theta given y. We can obtain this expression using the laws of conditional probability and specifically using Bayesâ€™ theorem.
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y) &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)}{\mathbb{P}r(y)}
\\ &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)}{\int \mathbb{P}r(\theta,y)}
\\ &= \frac{\mathbb{P}r(y \mid \theta)\ \mathbb{P}r(\theta)}{\int \mathbb{P}r(y \mid \theta)\ \mathbb{P}r(\theta)\ d\theta}
\end{aligned}
We start with the definition of conditional probability (1). The conditional distribution, \mathbb{P}r(\theta \mid y) is the ratio of the joint distribution of \theta and y, i.e.Â \mathbb{P}r(\theta,y); with the marginal distribution of y, \mathbb{P}r(y).
To make this look like the Bayes theorem that weâ€™re familiar with the joint distribution can be rewritten as the product of the prior and the likelihood. We start with the likelihood, because thatâ€™s how we usually write Bayesâ€™ theorem. We have the same thing in the denominator here. But weâ€™re going to integrate over the values of theta. These integrals are replaced by summations if we know that \theta is a discrete random variable. The marginal distribution is another important piece which we may use when we more advanced Bayesian modeling.
The posterior distribution is our primary tool for achieving the statistical modeling objectives from lesson one.

88.3 Differencing and smoothing ðŸ“–
 Differencing and smoothing are techniques used to remove trends and seasonality in time series data. They are covered in the (Prado, Ferreira, and West 2023, sec. 1.4).
Many synthetic time series models are built under the assumption of stationarity. However, in the real world time series data often present non-stationary features such as trends or seasonality. These features render such a time series non-stationary, and therefore, not suitable for analysis using the tools and methods we have discussed so far. However practitioners can use techniques for detrending, deseasonalizing and smoothing that when applied to such observed data transforms it into a new time series that is consistent with the stationarity assumption.
We briefly discuss two methods that are commonly used in practice for detrending and smoothing.

88.3.1 Differencing
Differencing, is a method which removes the trend from a time series data. The first difference of a time series is defined in terms of the difference operator, denoted as D, that produces the transformation differencing operator D

Dy_t \doteqdot y_t - y_{t-1}
\tag{88.16}
Higher order differences are obtained by successively applying the operator D. For example,

D^2y_t = D(Dy_t) = D(y_t - y_{t-1}) = y_t - 2y_{t-1} + y_{t-2}
\tag{88.17}
Differencing can also be written in terms of the so called back-shift operator B, with back-shift operator B

By_t \doteqdot y_{t-1},
\tag{88.18}
so that

Dy_t \doteqdot (1 - B) y_t
\tag{88.19}
and

D^dy_t \doteqdot (1 - B)^d y_t.
\tag{88.20}
this notation lets us write the differences in by referencing items backwards in time, which is often more intuitive and also useful, for example, when we will want to write the differencing operator in terms of a polynomial.


88.3.2 Smoothing
 Moving averages, which is commonly used to â€œsmoothâ€ a time series by removing certain features (e.g., seasonality) to highlight other features (e.g., trends).
A moving average is a weighted average of the time series around a particular time t. In general, if we have data y_{1:T}, we could obtain a new time series such that moving average

z_t = \sum_{j=-q}^{p} w_j y_{t+j} \qquad
\tag{88.21}
for t = (q + 1) : (T âˆ’ p), with weights w_j \ge 0 and \sum^p_{j=âˆ’q} w_j = 1
We will frequently work with moving averages for which

p = q \qquad \text{(centered)}

and

w_j = w_{âˆ’j} \forall j  \text{(symmetric)}

Assume we have periodic data with period d. Then, symmetric and centered moving averages can be used to remove such periodicity as follows:

If d = 2q :


z_t =  \frac{1}{d} \left(\frac{1}{2} y_{tâˆ’q} + y_{tâˆ’q+1} + \ldots + y_{t+qâˆ’1} + \frac{1}{2} y_{t+q}\right )
\tag{88.22}

if d = 2q + 1 :


z_t = \frac{1}{d} \left( y_{tâˆ’q} + y_{tâˆ’q+1} + \ldots + y_{t+qâˆ’1} + y_{t+q}\right )
\tag{88.23}

Example 88.1 (Seasonal Moving Average) To remove seasonality in monthly data (i.e., seasonality with a period of d = 12 months), we use a moving average with p = q = 6, a_6 = a_{âˆ’6} = 1/24, and a_j = a_{âˆ’j} = 1/12 for j = 0, \ldots , 5 , resulting in:

z_t = \frac{1}{24} y_{tâˆ’6} + \frac{1}{12}y_{tâˆ’5} + \ldots + \frac{1}{12}y_{t+5} + \frac{1}{24}y_{t+6}
\tag{88.24}

