TipHistorical Note on The William Sealy Gosset A.K.A Student



 The student-t distribution is due to Gosset, William Sealy (1876-1937) who was an English statistician, chemist and brewer who served as Head Brewer of Guinness and Head Experimental Brewer of Guinness and was a pioneer of modern statistics. He is known for his pioneering work on small sample experimental designs. Gosset published under the pseudonym â€œStudentâ€ and developed most famously Studentâ€™s t-distribution â€“ originally called Studentâ€™s â€œzâ€ â€“ and â€œStudentâ€™s test of statistical significanceâ€.
He was told to use a Pseudonym and choose â€˜Studentâ€™ after a predecessor at Guinness published a paper that leaked trade secrets. Gosset was a friend of both Karl Pearson and Ronald Fisher. Fisher suggested a correction to the student-t using the degrees of freedom rather than the sample size. Fisher is also credited with helping to publicize its use.
for a full biography see (Pearson et al. 1990)

