108.2 Natural Logarithms
We will need to manipulate long products of probabilities. Since there often comprise small fractions, their calculation on computers can be problematic due to the underflow of floats. We will therefore prefer to convert these products into sums of logarithms.

Definition 108.1 (The Logarithm) A log is the inverse of a power. We can use (EquationÂ 108.1).

y = a^x \implies log_a(y) = x
\tag{108.1}


Definition 108.2 (The Natural log) The natural logarithm function has base e and is written without the subscript

log_e(y) = log(y)
\tag{108.2}


Theorem 108.1 (Logs take positive values) logs only exist for values greater than 0

\forall x(e^x &gt; 0) \implies \exists \log(y) \iff {y &gt; 0}


We can use the properties of exponents from the previous section to obtain some important properties of logarithms:

Definition 108.3 (Log of a product) we can use EquationÂ 108.3 to convert a log of a product to a sum of logs.

\log(xÂ·y) = \log(x) + \log(y)
\tag{108.3}


Definition 108.4 (Log of a quotient) we can use EquationÂ 108.4 to convert a log of a quotient to a difference of logs.

\log(\frac{x}{y}) = log(x) âˆ’ log(y)
\tag{108.4}


Definition 108.5 (Log of a power) we can use EquationÂ 108.5 to convert a log of a variable raised to a power into the product.

    \log(x^b) = b \cdot log(x)
\tag{108.5}


Definition 108.6 (Log of one) we can use (EquationÂ 108.6) to replace a log of 1 with zero since $x(x^0 = 1) $

    \log(1)=0
\tag{108.6}


108.2.1 Log of exponent
we can use (EquationÂ 108.7) to cancel a log of an exponent since the log is the inverse function of the exponent.

exp(log(y)) = log(exp(y)) = y
\tag{108.7}

Example 108.1 (Logarithm) 
    \begin{aligned}
    log \frac{5^2}{10}= 2 log(5) âˆ’ log(10) â‰ˆ 0.916.
    \end{aligned}



Definition 108.7 (Change of base for a log) we can use (EquationÂ 108.8) to change the base of a logarithm.

    \log_b(a)=\frac{\log_c(a)}{\log_c(n)}
\tag{108.8}


Definition 108.8 (Derivative of a Log) we can use (EquationÂ 108.9) to differentiate a log.

    \frac{d}{dx} \log_(x)=\frac{1}{x}
\tag{108.9}


Because the natural logarithm is a monotonically increasing one-to-one function, finding the x which maximizes any (positive-valued function) f(x) is equivalent to maximizing log(f(x)).
This is useful because we often take derivatives to maximize functions.
If f(x) has product terms, then log(f(x)) will have summation terms, which are usually simpler when taking derivatives.

